ost-split conversion rate:** 1 share of Preferred Stock → **50 shares of Common Stock**\n- **Implied pre-split conversion rate:** 10 shares of Common Stock per Preferred Share (10 × 5 = 50)\n- **Series-specific Initial Prices** (all on post-split basis): Series G ($77.46), Series H ($135.00), Series I ($169.00), Series J ($186.00), Series K ($204.00), Series L ($214.00), Series M ($220.00), Series N ($270.00)\n- **Implied post-split common stock values** (Initial Price ÷ 50) range from $1.5492 (Series G) to $5.4000 (Series N)\n\n### D. Stock Option Exercise Prices\n\nAll historical exercise prices are stated on a split-adjusted basis. Specific grants cited include:\n- $37.00 per share (May 2025 grants)\n- $42.40 per share (October 2025 grants)\n- $19.40 per share (earlier grants)\n\nThese are all **post-split** exercise prices. The pre-split equivalents would be 5× higher (e.g., $185.00 and $212.00 respectively).\n\n### E. RSU/RSA Grant-Date Fair Values\n\n- **RSU weighted-average grant-date fair value (FY 2025):** $54.84/share (post-split)\n- **RSA weighted-average grant-date fair value (FY 2025):** $93.87/share (post-split)\n- **CEO RSA grant-date fair value (Jan 2026):** $90.40–$95.92/share (post-split)\n\n### F. Share-Based Compensation\n\n- Total remaining unrecognized share-based compensation expense: $4,842 million (weighted-average vesting period of 3.2 years)\n- Shares reserved for future grants: 543.8 million (post-split basis)\n- ESPP discount: 85% of FMV on offering date or purchase date (whichever is lower), with all FMV references on a post-split basis\n\n### G. Pro Forma Dilution Table (IPO-Specific)\n\n- **Pro forma net tangible book value per share** (as of March 31, 2026) — blank in filing, pending IPO pricing\n- **Dilution in net tangible book value per share to new investors** — blank in filing\n- **Average price per share** for existing vs. new investors — blank in filing\n\nAll of these are presented on a post-split basis once IPO price is determined.\n\n### H. Authorized Shares and Par Value\n\n- Class A Common: 36,132,150,000 authorized shares, $0.001 par value\n- Class B Common: 6,125,000,000 authorized shares, $0.001 par value\n- Class C Common: 10,000,000,000 authorized shares, $0.001 par value\n- Preferred Stock: 2,400,000,000 authorized shares, $0.001 par value\n\n---\n\n## 3. Why Analysts Must Apply the Adjustment Factor Before Drawing Valuation Conclusions\n\n### A. Ensuring Numerical Comparability\n\nAn analyst comparing Forge Global's pre-split $634 peak price to the S-1's per-share metrics without applying the 5:1 adjustment would commit a **5× valuation error**. For example:\n- Pre-split Forge Global price: **$634.00**\n- S-1 Q1 2026 diluted EPS: **$(1.27)** (post-split)\n- Implied P/E (without adjustment): $634 / $(1.27) = meaningless in this case, but for a positive-EPS period the ratio would be inflated 5×\n- Correct P/E: $126.80 / $(1.27) = correct comparison basis\n\n### B. Share Counts Are the Denominator for All Per-Share Metrics\n\nThe S-1 presents all weighted-average share counts (e.g., 2,926 million for FY 2025 basic, 3,884 million for Q1 2026 basic) on a post-split basis. If an analyst uses a pre-split share price but post-split share counts to calculate market capitalization, the result would be off by a factor of 5:\n- **Correct market cap:** Post-split price × Post-split shares = $126.80 × 3,884M = ~$492.5 billion\n- **Incorrect market cap:** Pre-split price × Post-split shares = $634 × 3,884M = ~$2.46 trillion (5× overstated)\n\n### C. Conversion Economics Require Consistent Basis\n\nThe preferred stock conversion rate (1:50) is stated on a post-split basis. The implied common stock value per preferred share ($1.5492–$5.40) must be compared to post-split common stock prices. Using pre-split prices would misrepresent conversion economics and liquidation preferences by a factor of 5.\n\n### D. Option and RSU Exercise Prices Must Be Compared on the Same Basis\n\nAll exercise prices in the S-1 ($37.00, $42.40, etc.) are post-split. To calculate intrinsic value of outstanding options:\n- **Correct:** Current post-split stock price – $37.00 exercise price\n- **Incorrect:** Current pre-split stock price – $37.00 exercise price (would massively overstate intrinsic value)\n\n### E. Secondary Market Prices Pre-Date the Split\n\nForge Global and other secondary market platforms quote pre-split prices until the split's effective date (May 4, 2026). Any transaction occurring before that date at $634/share represents the same economic interest as $126.80/share post-split. Failing to adjust creates an artificial appearance of 5× value appreciation when comparing pre-split transactions to post-split S-1 data.\n\n### F. ESPP Discount Calculation\n\nThe ESPP purchase price is 85% of the lower of FMV on the offering date or purchase date. All FMV references are on a post-split basis. An analyst modeling ESPP dilution using pre-split secondary market prices would overestimate the discount benefit by 5×.\n\n---\n\n## Summary Table\n\n| Metric | Pre-Split Value | Split Factor | Post-Split Value |\n|--------|----------------|--------------|------------------|\n| Forge Global peak price (Apr 1, 2026) | $634.00 | ÷ 5 | **$126.80** |\n| Preferred conversion rate | 10:1 | × 5 | 50:1 |\n| FY 2025 weighted-avg. basic shares | ~585M (est.) | × 5 | 2,926M |\n| Stock option exercise price example | $185.00 (est.) | ÷ 5 | $37.00 |\n| RSU avg. grant-date fair value example | $274.20 (est.) | ÷ 5 | $54.84 |\n\n---\n\n**Sources:**\n- SpaceX S-1 Filing (May 20, 2026): https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1181412/000162828026036936/spaceexplorationtechnologi.htm\n"
